01:12.400 --> 01:14.925
<i>Those were the years</i>
<i>after the ice caps had melted...</i>

01:15.036 --> 01:17.971
<i>because of</i>
<i>the greenhouse gases,</i>

01:18.073 --> 01:20.564
<i>and the oceans had risen</i>
<i>to drown so many cities...</i>

01:20.675 --> 01:23.610
<i>along all the shorelines</i>
<i>of the world.</i>

01:23.712 --> 01:27.910
<i>Amsterdam, Venice, New York...</i>

01:28.016 --> 01:29.916
<i>forever lost.</i>

01:30.018 --> 01:32.851
<i>Millions of people</i>
<i>were displaced.</i>

01:32.954 --> 01:35.821
<i>Climates became chaotic.</i>

01:35.924 --> 01:39.485
<i>Hundreds of millions of people</i>
<i>starved in poorer countries.</i>

01:39.594 --> 01:41.721
<i>Elsewhere, a high degree</i>
<i>of prosperity survived...</i>

01:41.830 --> 01:43.764
<i>when most governments</i>
<i>in the developed world...</i>

01:43.865 --> 01:48.199
<i>introduced legal sanctions to</i>
<i>strictly license pregnancies,</i>

01:48.303 --> 01:50.771
<i>which was why robots,</i>

01:50.872 --> 01:53.170
<i>who are never hungry and who</i>
<i>did not consume resources...</i>

01:53.274 --> 01:55.708
<i>beyond those</i>
<i>of their first manufacture,</i>

01:55.810 --> 01:59.473
<i>were so essential</i>
<i>an economic link...</i>

01:59.581 --> 02:01.811
<i>in the chain mail of society.</i>

02:01.916 --> 02:05.943
To create an artificial being
has been the dream of man...

02:06.054 --> 02:08.044
since the birth of science

02:09.657 --> 02:11.716
Not merely the beginning
of the modern age...

02:11.826 --> 02:15.421
when our forbearers astonished the
world with the first thinking machines...

02:15.530 --> 02:17.589
primitive monsters
that could play chess

02:17.699 --> 02:20.031
How far we have come

02:22.036 --> 02:24.197
The artificial being
is a reality...

02:24.305 --> 02:27.365
of perfect simulacrum...

02:27.475 --> 02:29.909
articulated in limb

02:30.011 --> 02:32.878
articulate in speech...

02:32.981 --> 02:35.176
and not lacking
in human response

02:41.156 --> 02:44.421
And even pain-memory response

02:49.197 --> 02:53.099
How did that make you feel?
Angry? Shocked?

02:53.201 --> 02:57.228
- I don't understand.
- What did I do to your feelings?

02:57.338 --> 02:59.238
You did it to my hand

03:00.809 --> 03:02.640
All right

03:04.078 --> 03:06.740
There's the rub

03:06.848 --> 03:10.807
Undress.
At Cybertronics of New Jersey

03:10.919 --> 03:13.854
the artificial being
has reached its highest form

03:13.955 --> 03:16.048
The universally-adopted Mecha…

03:16.157 --> 03:19.615
the basis for hundreds of models
serving the human race...

03:19.727 --> 03:22.252
in all the multiplicity
of daily life

03:22.363 --> 03:24.422
That's far enough

03:24.532 --> 03:27.592
But we have no reason
to congratulate ourselves

03:28.803 --> 03:32.899
We are rightly proud of it

03:33.007 --> 03:35.100
but what does it amount to?

03:35.210 --> 03:37.110
Sheila, open

03:56.731 --> 03:59.325
A sensory toy...

03:59.434 --> 04:02.733
with intelligent
behavioral circuits...

04:02.837 --> 04:05.772
using neurone-sequencing
technology...

04:05.874 --> 04:08.434
as old as I am

04:10.712 --> 04:16.082
I believe that my work on mapping the
impulse pathways in a single neurone...

04:16.184 --> 04:19.119
can enable us to construct...

04:19.220 --> 04:22.212
a Mecha of a qualitatively
different order

04:24.359 --> 04:26.827
I propose...

04:26.928 --> 04:29.158
that we build a robot...

04:30.832 --> 04:33.426
- who can love.
- Love?

04:35.136 --> 04:40.164
- But we ship thousands of lover models every month.
- Of course

04:40.275 --> 04:43.608
You're your own best customer,
Syatyoo-Sama.

04:43.711 --> 04:47.112
Quality control is very important.

04:58.660 --> 05:02.027
Tell me. What is love?

05:02.130 --> 05:04.758
Love is first widening
my eyes a little bit...

05:04.866 --> 05:06.766
and quickening my breathing
a little...

05:06.868 --> 05:08.768
and warming my skin
and touching my...

05:08.870 --> 05:10.997
And so on. Exactly so.
Thank you, Sheila

05:13.107 --> 05:15.974
But I wasn't referring
to sensuality simulators

05:16.077 --> 05:19.308
The word that I used was love.

05:19.414 --> 05:22.042
Love like the love of a child
for its parents

05:22.150 --> 05:26.780
I propose that we build
a robot child who can love

05:26.888 --> 05:29.686
A robot child
who will genuinely love…

05:29.791 --> 05:31.782
the parent or parents
it imprints on...

05:31.893 --> 05:33.793
with a love that will never end

05:33.895 --> 05:35.795
A child-substitute Mecha?

05:35.897 --> 05:39.890
But a Mecha with a mind,
with neuronal feedback

05:40.001 --> 05:43.232
You see, what I'm suggesting
is that love will be the key...

05:43.338 --> 05:47.001
by which they acquire a kind of
subconscious never before achieved

05:47.108 --> 05:49.770
An inner world of metaphor,
of intuition

05:49.877 --> 05:52.402
of self-motivated reasoning

05:52.513 --> 05:55.141
- of dreams.
- A robot that dreams?

05:55.249 --> 05:58.480
- Yes.
- How exactly do we pull this off?

05:58.586 --> 06:00.486
You know, it occurs to me...

06:00.588 --> 06:05.218
with all this animus
existing against Mechas today

06:05.326 --> 06:08.921
it isn't simply a question
of creating a robot who can love

06:09.030 --> 06:13.797
But isn't the real conundrum,
can you get a human to love them back?

06:13.901 --> 06:16.699
Ours will be a perfect child
caught in a freeze-frame...

06:16.804 --> 06:19.102
always loving,
never ill, never changing

06:19.207 --> 06:22.768
With all the childless couples
yearning in vain for a license

06:22.877 --> 06:25.641
our little Mecha will not only
open up a completely new market

06:25.747 --> 06:27.647
but it will fill
a great human need

06:27.749 --> 06:30.843
But you haven't answered
my question

06:30.952 --> 06:34.911
If a robot could genuinely
love a person

06:35.023 --> 06:39.653
what responsibility does that person
hold toward that Mecha in return?

06:41.396 --> 06:44.263
It's a moral question,
isn't it?

06:44.365 --> 06:46.560
The oldest one of all

06:46.667 --> 06:50.034
But in the beginning, didn't God
create Adam to love Him?

08:21.095 --> 08:24.155
<i>The baby was born</i>
<i>as the first leaves of autumn fell.</i>

08:24.265 --> 08:28.702
A baby boy.
And Marian's wish came true

08:28.803 --> 08:30.998
The boy had white hair

08:31.105 --> 08:34.938
He was baptized Martin,
after his grandfather

08:42.683 --> 08:45.379
- Dr. Frazier. Hi. Good to see you.
- Hello, Henry

08:45.486 --> 08:48.853
Listen, there was an article by Random
Bach in the <i>Journal of Chinese Medicine.</i>

08:48.956 --> 08:51.151
- They talked about these virus locators,
- Hello again, Monica

08:51.259 --> 08:53.159
Microscopic synthetic
hunter killers

08:53.261 --> 08:55.252
<i>- Did you read that article?</i>
- I can still hear you

09:00.368 --> 09:03.098
- I'm worried about her, Henry. She's really got me worried.
- Yeah, I know

09:03.204 --> 09:05.138
She's in the most difficult
position of feeling...

09:05.239 --> 09:07.571
she should mourn
the death of your son

09:07.675 --> 09:11.042
After five years, your instincts
tell you to mourn him too

09:11.145 --> 09:13.705
But medicine assures us that
mourning is inappropriate...

09:13.814 --> 09:16.715
- that Martin is merely pending.
- Pending

09:19.554 --> 09:22.182
So all her grief
goes undigested

09:25.726 --> 09:28.786
Henry, your son
may be beyond our science

09:28.896 --> 09:30.887
but it's your wife
who can still be reached

09:42.476 --> 09:44.842
The screening process
was extremely difficult

09:44.946 --> 09:47.073
It was almost tougher
than building the prototype

09:47.181 --> 09:49.149
Of our 2,000 employees,
a surprising few...

09:49.250 --> 09:51.514
met your minimum requirements
for the in-house testing

09:51.619 --> 09:55.248
Initiate. Employment record,
quality of lifestyle...

09:55.356 --> 09:58.655
Query, internal data...

09:58.759 --> 10:03.890
loyalty to the firm,
and in this individual's case

10:03.998 --> 10:07.729
a family tragedy
that may qualify him above the rest

10:11.639 --> 10:13.334
I'll see him

10:17.812 --> 10:19.712
- Henry!
- Don't kill me

10:19.814 --> 10:21.782
Henry, what are you doing?

10:23.985 --> 10:26.715
I love you. Don't kill me

10:29.290 --> 10:31.190
The door's closed

11:10.398 --> 11:12.423
I like your floor

11:23.377 --> 11:25.845
I can't accept this!

11:25.946 --> 11:28.244
There is no substitute
for your own child!

11:28.349 --> 11:31.409
You don't have to accept it or even try.
It's not too late to take him back

11:31.519 --> 11:33.419
What were you thinking?

11:33.521 --> 11:35.546
- I'll do whatever you want me to do.
- Do you think I can just...

11:35.656 --> 11:39.558
- I can just...
- I'll do whatever you want me to do!

11:39.660 --> 11:42.026
I don't know what to do

11:42.129 --> 11:46.293
I know, I know. I'll return him to
Cybertronics first thing in the morning

11:46.400 --> 11:48.300
It's gone

11:50.838 --> 11:53.136
Good

11:53.240 --> 11:55.208
I mean, Henry,
did you see his face?

11:55.309 --> 11:57.470
He's...

11:57.578 --> 11:59.478
He's so real

12:01.749 --> 12:04.547
- But he's not.
- No, he's not

12:04.652 --> 12:07.485
I mean, inside he's like
all the rest, isn't he?

12:07.588 --> 12:09.749
A hundred miles of fiber, yeah

12:12.193 --> 12:15.185
But outside,
he just looks so real...

12:17.965 --> 12:20.263
like he is a child

12:21.569 --> 12:23.969
A Mecha child

12:30.344 --> 12:32.244
A child

13:06.080 --> 13:10.540
The show of faith my company has
placed on me, on us, is extraordinary

13:10.651 --> 13:12.949
Now, there are a few simple
procedures we need to follow...

13:13.053 --> 13:15.351
if and when
you decide to keep David

13:15.456 --> 13:17.981
If you decide to keep him,
there's an imprinting protocol...

13:18.092 --> 13:20.356
consisting of a code string
of seven particular words...

13:20.461 --> 13:23.919
which need to be spoken to David in the
predefined order that's been printed here

13:24.031 --> 13:26.261
Now, Monica,
for our own protection

13:26.367 --> 13:28.528
this imprinting is irreversible

13:28.636 --> 13:30.968
The robot child's love would be
sealed... in a sense, hardwired...

13:31.071 --> 13:33.005
and would be
part of him forever

13:33.107 --> 13:35.007
Because of this,
after imprinting

13:35.109 --> 13:37.134
no Mecha child can be resold

13:37.244 --> 13:39.678
If an adopted parent should
ever decide not to keep the child

13:39.780 --> 13:42.977
they must return it
to Cybertronics for destruction

13:43.083 --> 13:47.247
I had to sign a letter of agreement,
or they wouldn't even let you see David

13:47.354 --> 13:49.254
You have to sign it too.
Right here

13:50.825 --> 13:55.262
Monica, don't imprint
until you're entirely sure

13:56.730 --> 14:00.257
Silly man.
Of course I'm not sure

14:28.362 --> 14:30.592
Would you like me to sleep now?

14:31.932 --> 14:33.923
Good idea. Good idea.

14:34.034 --> 14:37.629
- Monica?
- Well, it's late, you know

14:37.738 --> 14:40.206
- It's after 9:00, so...
- Yeah. Ten past

14:40.307 --> 14:43.606
How-How late
do they let you stay up?

14:43.711 --> 14:45.838
I can never go to sleep

14:45.946 --> 14:49.473
But I can lay quietly
and not make a peep

14:49.583 --> 14:53.576
So, those pajamas will fit you, and we'll be
in to check on you first thing in the morning

14:53.687 --> 14:55.678
Dress me?

14:55.789 --> 14:59.816
You know, I'm gonna say good night
while you boys be boys

15:03.964 --> 15:05.864
Raise your arms

17:42.990 --> 17:45.015
- Is it a game?
- Yes

17:46.427 --> 17:49.123
Hide-and-seek

17:49.229 --> 17:51.129
I found you

17:53.133 --> 17:55.624
That's your room.
Just, go and play

18:16.690 --> 18:19.921
I found you

18:20.027 --> 18:22.757
Out! Out! Get out of here!

18:22.863 --> 18:25.127
And close the goddamn door!

20:08.502 --> 20:12.063
<i>I can't...</i>

22:14.995 --> 22:17.122
Is it a game?

22:17.230 --> 22:19.425
Now, I'm gonna read some words

22:19.533 --> 22:22.525
And, they won't make any sense

22:22.636 --> 22:25.070
but I want you to
listen to them anyway...

22:25.172 --> 22:28.539
and look at me all the time

22:28.642 --> 22:32.601
- Can you do that?
- Yes, Monica

22:38.352 --> 22:41.651
Can you feel my hand
on the back of your neck?

22:41.755 --> 22:43.882
Yes

22:43.991 --> 22:46.721
- Does any of this hurt?
- No

22:46.827 --> 22:50.422
Okay, now, look at me

22:52.032 --> 22:53.932
Ready?

22:56.903 --> 22:58.803
Cirrus

23:01.041 --> 23:02.872
Socrates

23:05.045 --> 23:06.945
Particle

23:08.682 --> 23:10.946
Decibel

23:12.786 --> 23:14.651
Hurricane

23:14.755 --> 23:16.655
Dolphin

23:18.392 --> 23:20.292
Tulip

23:22.396 --> 23:24.296
Monica

23:26.466 --> 23:29.094
David

23:29.202 --> 23:31.102
Monica

23:42.482 --> 23:44.382
All right

23:46.053 --> 23:49.614
I wonder if I did that right.
I don't...

23:50.891 --> 23:53.052
What were those words for,
Mommy?

23:58.031 --> 23:59.931
What did you call me?

24:01.668 --> 24:03.533
Mommy

24:05.906 --> 24:08.306
Who am I, David?

24:12.412 --> 24:14.539
You are my mommy

24:36.536 --> 24:39.232
You smell lovely

24:39.339 --> 24:41.239
I love it when
you wear this stuff

24:41.341 --> 24:43.775
- Will you still love me when it's all gone?
- No

24:43.877 --> 24:45.868
- Stop it.
- But we can get married again...

24:45.979 --> 24:48.880
and begin with a fragrance
that's not in such short supply

24:48.982 --> 24:50.950
We gotta go.
Come on. We're late

24:54.788 --> 24:56.847
- Hello, David.
- Hello, Henry

24:56.957 --> 24:59.016
- Walk us out, all right, sweetheart?
- Come on

25:01.728 --> 25:03.821
My shoe!

25:09.136 --> 25:11.195
<i>- Henry, your tie!</i>
<i>- I know, I know.</i>

25:11.304 --> 25:13.204
<i>You're hopeless!</i>

25:13.306 --> 25:16.798
<i>He's trying so hard</i>
<i>to please me.</i>

25:16.910 --> 25:20.141
- He has a way with my coffee.
- And it's creepy

25:20.247 --> 25:23.774
- You can never hear him coming. He's just always there.
- He is only a child

25:23.884 --> 25:26.478
Monica, he's a toy

25:26.586 --> 25:28.884
He's a gift...

25:28.989 --> 25:30.889
from you

25:32.559 --> 25:36.051
David, when we leave, all the doors
and windows will go smart

25:36.163 --> 25:39.223
So you can't leave your room.
But if you'd like...

25:39.332 --> 25:42.358
- Oh, I put way too much on.
- Do I smell lovely?

25:45.605 --> 25:47.505
Oh, God, no

25:59.386 --> 26:01.411
<i>Mommy,</i>

26:01.521 --> 26:03.421
will you die?

26:08.261 --> 26:11.389
Well, one day, David,
yes, I will

26:16.603 --> 26:19.128
I'll be alone

26:19.239 --> 26:21.207
Don't worry yourself so

26:31.751 --> 26:33.651
How long will you live?

26:35.522 --> 26:38.218
For ages

26:38.325 --> 26:41.260
For 50 years

26:41.361 --> 26:43.556
I love you, Mommy

26:45.098 --> 26:47.566
I hope you never die

26:48.935 --> 26:50.835
Never

26:53.807 --> 26:56.776
- Yes.
<i>- Darling!</i>

26:56.876 --> 27:00.004
We're becoming unfashionably,
unreasonably late

27:03.984 --> 27:05.884
Hello?

27:26.806 --> 27:29.434
This belonged to Martin, my son

27:57.671 --> 27:59.605
His name is Teddy

27:59.706 --> 28:01.606
Teddy, this is David

28:03.610 --> 28:06.909
- Hello, Teddy.
- Hello, David

28:07.013 --> 28:08.913
David, Teddy is a super toy

28:09.015 --> 28:12.109
and I know you will take
good care of each other

28:12.218 --> 28:14.448
I am <i>not</i> a toy

28:15.989 --> 28:18.389
<i>Henry?</i>

28:18.491 --> 28:20.584
- Sorry.
- What were you doing up there?

28:20.694 --> 28:23.390
I'll tell you in the car.
Come on

28:33.640 --> 28:36.768
Is 50 years a long time?

28:40.613 --> 28:42.513
I don't think so

28:43.183 --> 28:44.514
David, I'll get it!

28:53.693 --> 28:55.593
Honey, hand it to me

28:55.695 --> 28:58.186
Look what I can do

29:04.571 --> 29:06.471
Hello?

29:06.573 --> 29:09.303
Yes?

29:09.409 --> 29:11.536
Mrs. Swinton,
could you hold a moment?

29:11.644 --> 29:13.544
I have an urgent call
from your husband

29:13.646 --> 29:16.774
Yes, I will. David, I-I need
to talk to the phone now

29:16.883 --> 29:20.410
Monica?
Monica? Can you hear me, Monica?

29:20.520 --> 29:23.956
- Let the phone talk now.
- Monica, can you hear me? Pick up the phone, Monica!

29:24.057 --> 29:27.652
- Run along. Play with Teddy.
- Pick up the phone, Monica! Oh, my God! Mon¡

29:29.095 --> 29:31.256
Hello, Henry?
What is it? What...

29:32.866 --> 29:35.232
What?

29:35.335 --> 29:37.235
When?

29:39.739 --> 29:41.639
Oh, God

29:57.724 --> 29:59.783
David

29:59.893 --> 30:03.021
the most wonderful thing
in the whole world has happened

30:06.699 --> 30:09.497
This is Martin

30:09.602 --> 30:11.502
This is my son

30:27.053 --> 30:28.953
Martin, no!

30:32.959 --> 30:36.053
We'll have a contest
to see who he comes to first

30:41.901 --> 30:43.960
Come here, Teddy!
Come here, boy!

30:44.070 --> 30:46.868
<i>Teddy! Come here!</i>

30:46.973 --> 30:48.873
You call him too

30:50.777 --> 30:52.677
Come here, Teddy

30:52.779 --> 30:55.714
<i>- Come on! Teddy! Teddy!</i>
- Come here, boy

30:55.815 --> 30:59.376
- Come here! Come on, Teddy!
- Come here, Teddy

30:59.486 --> 31:02.080
<i>- Teddy. Come here, Teddy.</i>
<i>- Teddy, come!</i>

31:02.188 --> 31:04.486
- Come here, Teddy.
- Come, Teddy! Come!

31:08.695 --> 31:10.595
Mommy! Mommy!

31:14.868 --> 31:17.769
Are they torturing you, Teddy?

31:17.871 --> 31:22.672
He used to be a super toy,
but now he's old and stupid

31:25.879 --> 31:28.279
You want him?

31:28.381 --> 31:30.281
Yes, please

31:30.383 --> 31:32.681
So I guess now
you're the new super toy

31:32.785 --> 31:34.719
So, what good stuff can you do?

31:34.821 --> 31:39.190
Oh, can you do power stuff,
like walk on the ceiling or the walls?

31:39.292 --> 31:42.227
Anti-gravity?
Like, float or fly?

31:42.328 --> 31:45.058
Can you?

31:45.164 --> 31:49.260
No, because I'm <i>real.</i>

31:57.210 --> 32:00.805
- Can you break this?
- I better not

32:00.914 --> 32:04.475
These things, they do look better
in pieces. They do

32:04.584 --> 32:06.575
I can't

32:11.891 --> 32:13.791
Stand up

32:20.099 --> 32:23.830
Look, they made you
bigger than me

32:23.937 --> 32:26.405
- Who did?
- Well, they did... the doll makers

32:26.506 --> 32:28.406
They made you taller

32:32.679 --> 32:34.670
Why don't you look like one?

32:34.781 --> 32:37.272
Like one?

32:37.383 --> 32:41.080
You're not cute like a doll

32:41.187 --> 32:43.747
You just look like
someone's ordinary kid

32:46.392 --> 32:48.986
When's your birthday?

32:49.095 --> 32:50.995
I never had a birthday

32:51.097 --> 32:53.463
Okay. When were
you first built?

32:53.566 --> 32:55.466
When's your build-day?

32:57.837 --> 32:59.737
I don't remember

33:02.575 --> 33:05.635
Okay, what's the first thing
you can remember?

33:09.882 --> 33:12.715
- A bird.
- What sort of bird?

33:15.755 --> 33:19.020
A bird with big wings...

33:19.125 --> 33:21.787
and feathers sticking up
from the bottom

33:21.894 --> 33:23.794
Can you draw it?

33:23.896 --> 33:26.330
Yes

33:45.518 --> 33:47.418
<i>That looks like a peacock.</i>

33:47.520 --> 33:50.250
Can you say peacock?

33:50.356 --> 33:53.723
- Peacock.
- Can you say pee?

33:53.826 --> 33:56.989
- Pee.
- Now say that two times fast

34:07.907 --> 34:10.034
<i>Okay.</i>

34:10.143 --> 34:12.110
<i>Then you gotta put</i>
<i>the green ones...</i>

34:12.210 --> 34:15.237
- Read to us?
- Hey

34:15.348 --> 34:17.248
Let's see

34:19.452 --> 34:21.351
Oh, yeah

34:26.458 --> 34:29.518
David's going to <i>love</i> it

34:31.731 --> 34:35.063
As soon as his show was over,
the showman went into the kitchen

34:35.168 --> 34:37.636
where the whole sheep which
he was preparing for supper...

34:37.737 --> 34:40.900
was roasting on
the slowly-turning spit in the furnace

34:41.007 --> 34:43.873
When he saw there was not
enough wood to finish roasting it

34:43.976 --> 34:47.377
he called Harlequin
and the Punchinello and said

34:47.480 --> 34:51.416
'Bring me in Pinocchio.
You will find him hanging on a nail

34:51.516 --> 34:53.417
'He is made of nice, dry wood

34:53.518 --> 34:55.953
and I'm sure he will make
a nice fire for my roast.'

34:56.054 --> 34:58.751
<i>Pinocchio worked</i>
<i>until midnight.</i>

34:58.858 --> 35:01.520
<i>And instead of making</i>
<i>eight baskets,</i>

35:01.627 --> 35:04.721
<i>he made sixteen.</i>

35:04.831 --> 35:08.631
<i>Then he went to bed</i>
<i>and fell asleep.</i>

35:08.735 --> 35:14.002
As he slept, he dreamt he saw
the fairy, lovely and smiling

35:14.107 --> 35:16.473
who gave him a kiss, saying

35:16.576 --> 35:18.476
'Brave Pinocchio

35:18.578 --> 35:24.210
<i>'in return for your good heart,</i>
<i>I forgive all your past misdeeds.</i>

35:24.317 --> 35:27.912
<i>Be good in future,</i>
<i>and you will be happy. '</i>

35:28.020 --> 35:31.956
Then the dream ended
and Pinocchio awoke

35:32.058 --> 35:34.322
full of amazement

35:34.427 --> 35:36.520
<i>You can imagine</i>
<i>how astonished he was...</i>

35:36.629 --> 35:40.622
<i>when he saw that he was</i>
<i>no longer a puppet...</i>

35:40.733 --> 35:44.829
<i>but a real boy</i>
<i>just like other boys.</i>

35:50.109 --> 35:53.704
Josephine evidently
has taken a leave of absence

35:53.813 --> 35:55.747
Oh, my God.

35:55.848 --> 35:59.409
<i>- Well, I saw that coming.</i>
<i>- How could you see that coming?</i>

35:59.519 --> 36:03.011
<i>- They were fabulous together.
- Oh, come on! She was miserable! I mean...</i>

36:03.122 --> 36:05.556
<i>- Well, he never said they were miserable.
- Yeah, that's because...</i>

36:05.658 --> 36:07.592
<i>Wasn't that</i>
<i>because of the cutbacks?</i>

36:07.693 --> 36:11.652
<i>I have no idea.</i>
<i>Actually, they don't tell me anything.</i>

36:11.764 --> 36:15.723
<i>- Do they really have a weight problem?</i>
<i>- So do I.</i>

36:15.835 --> 36:20.101
<i>- You do not. That is ridiculous.</i>
<i>- All right, look.</i>

36:20.206 --> 36:23.539
<i>I don't know. There's something</i>
<i>about inner beauty that...</i>

36:24.477 --> 36:26.377
You will break

36:26.479 --> 36:29.175
- Oh, that is ridiculous!
- Exactly

36:29.282 --> 36:33.742
<i>Work has become so silly.</i>

36:33.853 --> 36:35.753
I know what
you're talking about

36:42.995 --> 36:46.396
- Does he eat?
- I'm not sure

36:46.499 --> 36:49.297
<i>You're not supposed to do that.</i>
<i>David, what are you doing?</i>

36:49.402 --> 36:51.666
- David! Martin, put the fork down.
- Is it in the manual book?

36:51.771 --> 36:54.604
- Stop. Stop, David.
- Put it down now. David, stop it!

36:54.707 --> 36:57.608
<i>Martin, you're provoking him,</i>
<i>okay? Stop it.</i>

36:57.710 --> 36:59.735
- Stop it, David!
- The two of you, stop it!

36:59.846 --> 37:02.747
<i>Stop it! Stop it now!</i>

37:02.849 --> 37:05.909
Stop it! David, stop it!

37:28.441 --> 37:30.341
There's sputum
in the code lockers

37:30.443 --> 37:32.343
Smell that garlic

37:32.445 --> 37:34.879
We should throw in a chest mint

37:34.981 --> 37:37.506
- Can you locate the service?
- Don't touch the merchandise

37:39.585 --> 37:43.954
- It's all swamp in here.
<i>- You made a mess of yourself.</i>

37:47.226 --> 37:50.787
Spinach is for rabbits,
people and Popeye

37:50.897 --> 37:53.491
not robo-boys

37:53.599 --> 37:55.794
Try to insert yourself

37:57.470 --> 37:59.370
Now through the pantry,
all the lower shelves

37:59.472 --> 38:03.670
It's okay, Mommy.
It doesn't hurt

38:07.880 --> 38:10.713
The activators are
all shut down on the left side

38:12.718 --> 38:14.948
- Monica.
- I have to...

38:15.054 --> 38:17.045
I have to...

38:24.664 --> 38:28.327
That's not all of it.
That's not all of it

38:30.436 --> 38:34.998
<i>If you do something really,</i>
<i>really, really special for me,</i>

38:36.208 --> 38:39.143
a special mission

38:39.245 --> 38:41.941
then I'll go tell Mommy...

38:42.048 --> 38:44.608
<i>I</i> love you

38:44.717 --> 38:47.151
And then she'll love you too

38:50.489 --> 38:52.923
What shall I do?

38:53.025 --> 38:56.358
You have to promise,
and then I'll tell you

38:57.563 --> 39:01.966
You have to tell me,
and then I'll promise

39:03.769 --> 39:06.363
I want a lock of Mommy's hair

39:07.473 --> 39:09.373
I'll share it with you

39:09.475 --> 39:12.774
And if you had it and wore it

39:12.878 --> 39:14.903
she might love you even more

39:15.014 --> 39:18.177
Like the princess
in the movie we saw

39:18.284 --> 39:22.380
When she had the prince's hair
in her necklace thing

39:22.488 --> 39:24.581
he loved her

39:24.690 --> 39:26.590
We can ask her

39:26.692 --> 39:31.493
No, it has to be
a secret mission

39:31.597 --> 39:36.432
Sneak into Mommy's bedroom
in the middle of the night...

39:36.535 --> 39:39.026
and chop it off

39:44.343 --> 39:48.177
I can't, Martin.
I'm not allowed

39:48.280 --> 39:50.942
You promised

39:51.050 --> 39:55.487
You said, Tell me,
and then I'll promise.

39:55.588 --> 39:58.455
Didn't you?

41:05.091 --> 41:07.184
David!

41:09.195 --> 41:12.096
Why did you do that?
Why did you do that?

41:12.198 --> 41:14.758
- What are you doing? You're hurting him!
- Talk to me! Goddamn it!

41:14.867 --> 41:16.994
- Why did you do that? Why did you do that?
- You're hurting him!

41:17.103 --> 41:19.367
- You're hurting him! Don't break him!
- Why did you do that?

41:22.308 --> 41:26.711
Henry, I wanted Mommy
to love me...

41:26.812 --> 41:28.712
more

41:28.814 --> 41:30.805
- Oh, my God.
- What?

41:30.916 --> 41:34.283
- I think I cut my eye. Oh, God, I think it's bleeding.
- Let me see

41:42.061 --> 41:45.656
It's normal for little boys
to feel jealous and competitive

41:45.764 --> 41:50.827
Martin's only been home a month, and it's
normal for brothers to challenge each other

41:50.936 --> 41:53.769
He was playing a game,
he made a mistake, and...

41:53.873 --> 41:56.774
- He's practically human.
- That's not how he looked holding the knife

41:56.876 --> 41:59.470
- Scissors.
- It was a weapon

41:59.578 --> 42:01.944
Why do you keep imagining that
he was purposely trying to harm me?

42:02.047 --> 42:03.981
Because we don't know
the answer to that

42:04.083 --> 42:07.484
How is he worth the risk to you
or to Martin or to us as a family?

42:07.586 --> 42:10.180
I will not let you take him back.
You told me what would happen...

42:10.289 --> 42:12.484
- if we ever took him back.
- Think about this

42:12.591 --> 42:16.891
If he was created to love, then it's
reasonable to assume he knows how to hate

42:18.797 --> 42:21.857
And if pushed to those extremes,
what is he really capable of?

42:41.120 --> 42:43.020
Happy birthday, Martin

42:44.290 --> 42:46.190
I made this for you

42:50.329 --> 42:52.456
This him?
Is this your little brother?

42:52.565 --> 42:54.465
Technically, no

42:58.337 --> 43:01.135
- He's Mecha.
- What's Mecha?

43:01.240 --> 43:06.007
We're organic,
you're mechanical

43:06.111 --> 43:08.045
Orga, Mecha

43:08.147 --> 43:12.140
- Orga, Mecha. Orga, Mecha.
- Todd, stop!

43:12.251 --> 43:14.879
I didn't know
they even made little kids

43:14.987 --> 43:17.547
Can you pee?

43:17.656 --> 43:20.625
- I cannot.
- Then let's see what you <i>can't</i> pee with

43:20.726 --> 43:24.389
Come on

43:24.496 --> 43:26.828
Touch it

43:26.932 --> 43:29.765
It feels so real.
Oh, that's... that's creepy

43:29.868 --> 43:32.393
- It feels so real.
- That is too real

43:32.504 --> 43:34.404
Mecha-real

43:36.108 --> 43:38.008
Does he have DAS?

43:38.110 --> 43:40.305
- DAS what?
<i>- Das ist gut!</i>

43:40.412 --> 43:43.939
Damage Avoidance System. DAS

43:44.049 --> 43:46.074
It's a pain alert system

43:46.185 --> 43:48.085
Our serving man has it

43:48.187 --> 43:51.088
It's so they don't go picking up fire
with their bare hands and stuff

43:52.691 --> 43:54.852
Watch. Watch this

43:56.028 --> 43:58.394
Now, I'm not gonna cut you

43:58.497 --> 44:01.830
This isn't gonna hurt.
I'm not gonna cut your skin

44:01.934 --> 44:03.765
Just tell me when you feel it

44:07.973 --> 44:10.601
- Keep me safe, Martin. Keep me safe.
- Let me go!

44:10.709 --> 44:14.668
<i>- Keep me safe, Martin. Keep me safe. Keep me safe.</i>
- Let me go! Mom!

44:14.780 --> 44:18.477
<i>Mom! Mom!</i>

44:22.621 --> 44:26.387
Keep me safe. Keep me safe.
Keep me safe. Keep me safe

44:26.492 --> 44:28.653
Henry!

44:39.238 --> 44:41.536
Oh, my... Oh, my God!

44:52.084 --> 44:55.349
<i>Oh, my God! He's not</i>
<i>breathing! He's not breathing!</i>

44:59.258 --> 45:01.749
<i>Come on, Martin! Come on!</i>

45:01.860 --> 45:04.055
Take a breath. Take a breath.

45:04.163 --> 45:06.063
Cough it up. That a boy.
That's a great boy

45:06.165 --> 45:08.065
<i>Oh, my God. Thank God.</i>

45:42.835 --> 45:45.429
- Hey, David?
<i>- Mommy!</i>

45:45.537 --> 45:47.437
Mommy

45:47.539 --> 45:50.099
L-I need to speak to you
for a minute, okay?

45:51.377 --> 45:53.277
Okay

46:57.843 --> 46:59.743
These are beautiful

47:03.148 --> 47:05.048
Thank you

47:17.362 --> 47:19.489
Hey, David,
I was thinking that...

47:19.598 --> 47:22.692
we could go for a drive
tomorrow in the country

47:22.801 --> 47:25.770
You and me. What do you say?

47:25.871 --> 47:28.339
- And Teddy?
- Yeah, and Teddy

47:36.181 --> 47:38.081
Thank you, Mommy

47:39.184 --> 47:41.311
Thank you so much

47:49.862 --> 47:52.353
Tomorrow is gonna be
just for us, okay?

48:08.547 --> 48:10.447
Where are we going?

48:12.918 --> 48:14.818
Someplace nice?

48:21.059 --> 48:23.357
Are those happy tears?

48:27.332 --> 48:29.732
What's for dinner tonight?

48:30.903 --> 48:33.064
You know you don't eat

48:33.171 --> 48:35.071
Yes

48:36.642 --> 48:38.633
But I like sitting at the table

49:43.442 --> 49:46.673
David?
David, come on. David... David...

49:46.778 --> 49:48.678
Listen... Listen to me!

49:53.652 --> 49:55.643
David?

49:55.754 --> 49:57.813
David, listen

49:57.923 --> 50:00.983
Now...

50:01.093 --> 50:03.721
you won't understand
the reasons, but...

50:03.860 --> 50:06.294
I have...
I have to leave you here

50:07.997 --> 50:10.591
Is it a game?

50:10.700 --> 50:12.600
No

50:13.803 --> 50:16.738
When will you come back for me?

50:16.839 --> 50:19.831
I'm not, David. You'll have
to be here by yourself

50:22.111 --> 50:24.170
Alone?

50:26.049 --> 50:27.949
With Teddy

50:34.457 --> 50:37.756
No. No, no, no, no, no, no!

50:37.860 --> 50:39.760
No, Mommy, please!

50:39.862 --> 50:41.659
No, no! Please, no, Mommy!

50:41.764 --> 50:44.255
- They will destroy you.
- No! No, Mommy!

50:44.367 --> 50:46.426
I'm sorry I broke myself

50:46.536 --> 50:48.436
I'm so sorry
I cut your hair off...

50:48.538 --> 50:52.304
- and I'm sorry I hurt you and I hurt Martin.
- I have to go! I have to go!

50:52.408 --> 50:56.868
Stop it! Stop it!

50:56.979 --> 51:00.437
- I have to go now!
- Mommy, no! Mommy!

51:00.550 --> 51:03.610
Mommy, if Pinocchio
became a real boy...

51:03.720 --> 51:06.052
and I become a real boy,
can I come home?

51:06.155 --> 51:09.056
- That's just a story.
- But a story tells what happens

51:09.158 --> 51:13.322
Stories are not real!
You're not real!

51:18.935 --> 51:21.870
Now, listen to me. Look. Look!

51:21.971 --> 51:23.871
Take this, all right? Take this

51:23.973 --> 51:25.907
Don't let anyone see
how much it is

51:26.008 --> 51:27.942
Now, look, don't go that way

51:28.044 --> 51:30.308
Look! Look at me! Look!
Don't go that way, all right?

51:30.413 --> 51:34.008
Go anywhere but that way or they'll catch you.
Don't ever let them catch you!

51:34.117 --> 51:36.984
Listen, stay away
from flesh fairs

51:37.086 --> 51:39.054
away from where
there are lots of people

51:39.155 --> 51:42.283
Stay away from all people. Only others
like you. Only Mecha are safe

51:42.391 --> 51:44.655
- I gotta go.
- Why do you wanna leave me?

51:44.761 --> 51:48.788
Why do you wanna leave me?
I'm sorry I'm not real

51:48.898 --> 51:51.196
If you let me,
I'll be so real for you

51:51.300 --> 51:54.497
Let go. Let go, David. Let go!

52:00.209 --> 52:03.372
I'm sorry I didn't
tell you about the world

52:31.407 --> 52:34.570
<i>- I'm afraid.</i>
<i>- Of me?</i>

52:34.677 --> 52:38.738
<i>- Yes.</i>
<i>- That I will hurt you?</i>

52:38.848 --> 52:41.214
<i>Yes.</i>

52:41.317 --> 52:43.547
I think...

52:43.653 --> 52:46.053
you're afraid of letting go

52:47.523 --> 52:50.822
I think you're afraid
of happiness

52:50.927 --> 52:54.192
And this is starting
to excite me

52:56.065 --> 52:59.364
Are you afraid
of seeing the stars

52:59.468 --> 53:01.868
Patricia?

53:01.971 --> 53:03.939
I can show you
how to reach them

53:05.975 --> 53:08.705
I'm afraid of what
you've got under there

53:11.180 --> 53:13.740
May I see
what it looks like first?

53:15.852 --> 53:18.286
Is this your first time...

53:18.387 --> 53:20.287
with something like me?

53:21.924 --> 53:24.449
I've never been with Mecha

53:24.560 --> 53:26.460
That makes two of us

53:31.968 --> 53:34.232
I'm afraid it will hurt

53:35.338 --> 53:37.863
Patricia

53:37.974 --> 53:40.408
once you've had a lover robot

53:42.812 --> 53:47.146
you'll never want
a real man... again

53:52.388 --> 53:55.050
Are these the wounds
of passion?

54:01.831 --> 54:05.358
Are the stars out tonight

54:05.468 --> 54:09.700
- I don't know if it's cloudy or bright
- Do you hear that music?

54:09.805 --> 54:14.037
'Cause I only
have eyes for you, dear

54:14.143 --> 54:16.839
The moon may be high

54:16.946 --> 54:18.846
You...

54:18.948 --> 54:21.143
- 'Cause I only have eyes
- Are a goddess

54:21.250 --> 54:24.515
- For you
- Patricia

54:25.922 --> 54:28.356
You wind me up inside

54:30.159 --> 54:34.391
But you deserve
much better in your life

54:36.332 --> 54:38.892
You deserve...

54:41.003 --> 54:42.903
me

54:43.005 --> 54:46.736
'Cause I only have eyes for you

54:46.842 --> 54:48.605
Dear

54:48.711 --> 54:51.179
The moon may be high

54:51.280 --> 54:54.010
But I can't see a thing in the sky

54:54.116 --> 55:00.544
'Cause I only have eyes for you

55:22.645 --> 55:25.705
- Hey, Joe, what do ya know?
- Hi, Jane. How's the game?

55:31.053 --> 55:33.487
- Hey, Joe, what do ya know?
- Hello, Mr. Williamson

55:33.589 --> 55:37.616
- Place a D.N.D. On room 102, please.
- Sure thing

55:40.663 --> 55:42.563
There you are

55:42.665 --> 55:44.565
Oh, Joe

55:44.667 --> 55:49.104
When you're finished here, crack your
collar, show off your operating license

55:49.205 --> 55:54.006
The Flesh Fair's in Barn Creek and
the hounds are out hunting for strays

55:56.045 --> 55:58.912
It's a good thing I ran into you.
Thanks, Mr. Williamson

55:59.015 --> 56:01.916
- Sure thing.
- Mustn't keep a lady waiting

56:38.821 --> 56:40.721
Miss Bevins

56:42.124 --> 56:45.355
It's Joe. At your service

56:46.829 --> 56:49.992
I've been counting the seconds
since last we met

56:56.372 --> 56:59.364
Have you been crying, Samantha?

56:59.475 --> 57:01.739
I found a tear

57:11.420 --> 57:13.820
Hey, Joe, what do ya know?

57:16.258 --> 57:18.692
How many seconds has it been...

57:18.794 --> 57:22.457
the last time the two
of you were together?

57:22.565 --> 57:26.001
255,133

57:31.040 --> 57:34.601
Good-bye, Sam. And never forget

57:34.710 --> 57:37.270
You killed me first

57:43.752 --> 57:46.585
I'm in bad trouble

58:16.452 --> 58:19.751
<i>If I am a real boy,</i>

58:19.855 --> 58:22.790
<i>then I can go back.</i>

58:22.892 --> 58:25.224
And she will love me then

58:26.395 --> 58:28.295
How?

58:30.132 --> 58:33.295
The Blue Fairy made
Pinocchio into a real boy

58:34.970 --> 58:37.871
She can make me into a real boy

58:39.041 --> 58:43.068
I must find her.
I must become real

58:43.179 --> 58:47.673
There must be someone in the whole world
who knows where she lives

01:00:48.037 --> 01:00:51.131
Moon on the rise!

01:01:08.691 --> 01:01:13.492
It's the Flesh Fair. They destroy us
on stage. I've been there

01:01:15.864 --> 01:01:17.764
What do we do?

01:01:17.866 --> 01:01:20.562
We run now

01:01:22.404 --> 01:01:24.929
<i>Any old iron.</i>

01:01:26.175 --> 01:01:28.405
<i>Any old iron.</i>

01:01:30.946 --> 01:01:32.846
Any old iron

01:01:34.683 --> 01:01:36.583
Any old iron

01:01:37.886 --> 01:01:40.753
Expel your Mecha

01:01:40.856 --> 01:01:43.347
Purge yourselves
of artificiality

01:01:43.459 --> 01:01:45.950
Come along, now.
Let some Mecha loose to run

01:01:46.061 --> 01:01:49.121
Any old unlicensed iron
down there?

01:01:51.266 --> 01:01:53.757
Hey, do you see that?

01:01:53.869 --> 01:01:56.201
Could be a human thing

01:01:58.440 --> 01:02:00.567
No, he's scanning cold

01:02:00.676 --> 01:02:03.304
No expiration date, no I.D

01:02:03.412 --> 01:02:05.505
What's a new model doing
loose and unregistered?

01:02:05.614 --> 01:02:07.980
Sir, it's a late-generation
lover-Mecha

01:02:08.083 --> 01:02:11.541
Well, there's a relief
from all this antique iron

01:02:11.653 --> 01:02:13.621
You are certain he's not a man?

01:02:13.722 --> 01:02:16.156
<i>I wouldn't want a repeat</i>
<i>of the Trenton incident.</i>

01:02:16.258 --> 01:02:20.354
- Sir, he's a free-range Mecha running hot.
- Let's reel him in, boys

01:02:20.462 --> 01:02:22.396
Sic the hounds on the rest

01:02:53.395 --> 01:02:55.329
Shake down shantytown

01:04:02.097 --> 01:04:04.622
What's your name?

01:04:04.733 --> 01:04:08.134
- My name is David.
- Hello, David

01:04:08.237 --> 01:04:10.603
How old are you?

01:04:10.706 --> 01:04:12.606
I don't know

01:04:12.708 --> 01:04:15.472
You need someone
to take care of you?

01:04:15.577 --> 01:04:17.977
